“Don’t try this at home,” i mouth to myself as i lick my finger, blow on the marshmallow and place it on the top of the red-hot stick. Nyamachoma, the Swahili term for ‘roast meat’, is meat grilled to perfection over hot coals. In the streets of Dar es Salaam, a delicious dish of nyamachoma is only a stone’s throw away from the searing tropical heat. Unfortunately, the local’s penchant for spice masks the taste of the tender beef and local bonfire tongs ensure that several chunks end up on the ground. They are promptly devoured when they hit the ground. For $0.25 you aren’t getting much, but the value in worldview is unexpected. (On a side note, if you would like to hear a song Sunscreen that features lyrics about don’t try this at home, visit: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RZHj2NEy9z4&feature=PlayList&p=7E868291590401A6&index=0&playnext=1
